159
00:08:36,013 --> 00:08:38,054
on your product, you need to keep in mind

160
00:08:38,094 --> 00:08:39,375
some very important questions.

161
00:08:40,555 --> 00:08:42,957
Firstly, what were the specific issues raised?

162
00:08:44,077 --> 00:08:45,878
Secondly, what are you going to do

163
00:08:45,898 --> 00:08:47,939
about addressing these problems?

164
00:08:47,980 --> 00:08:49,120
Like, what do you need to do?

165
00:08:50,912 --> 00:08:55,296
I use these questions as a guide in writing my responses to comments, and I find them

166
00:08:55,316 --> 00:08:57,297
generally useful in my everyday messaging.

167
00:08:58,959 --> 00:09:03,903
A key point to remember is to communicate clearly your progress and process, such as

168
00:09:04,003 --> 00:09:07,647
is there any news on terms of fixes, update ETAs, etc.

169
00:09:09,488 --> 00:09:13,792
One of the things I did to help the community during my time at Wander is that I wrote FAQs

170
00:09:14,093 --> 00:09:17,616
and directed the community to them, which I did actually find quite helpful.

171
00:09:18,873 --> 00:09:20,854
Also when dealing with repetitive questions,

172
00:09:21,034 --> 00:09:22,835
I developed a template for responses

173
00:09:22,875 --> 00:09:26,456
which became the foundation for a reactive messaging system,

174
00:09:27,277 --> 00:09:29,417
an effective method I still use to this day.

175
00:09:30,938 --> 00:09:31,798
On a personal level,

176
00:09:32,599 --> 00:09:34,059
I was terrified I'd say something wrong.

177
00:09:34,840 --> 00:09:36,660
As we all know, the internet never forgets.

178
00:09:41,857 --> 00:09:47,439
In the first part of my response to Daryl, I try to empathize with him and try to build

179
00:09:47,459 --> 00:09:50,380
a relationship by acknowledging and understanding his point of view.

180
00:09:50,400 --> 00:09:56,222
